It’s a shame that self-aggrandisement comes too easily to us in matters giving. And social media has made the vice fester.
Clinton Onyango’s name may not be familiar to you but his story will be. A photo of the boy wearing torn sandals in school went viral this week. A Good Samaritan bought him a pair of shoes and posed for a photo for social media effect.





A touching gesture by any standards, but, as one person rightly pointed out in a WhatsApp group I belong to, it would be painful for the boy to go back to his classmates as the only one wearing shoes.
In his seminal autobiography The Boy with Shoes, Hillary Lisimba recounts how being the only boy with shoes in his village school made him an outsider and a subject of ridicule.
Clinton’s school and poverty-stricken family got the help that they needed from the public, but that’s not often the case. If the story had not caught the nation’s attention, he would have cut a lonesome figure in his “Toughees”.
The Starehe Boys Centre model of giving, as narrated by a former employee Maryana Munyendo during the WhatsApp debate, has nailed the art of giving.
“Part of our standard Form One reception package was a pair of Bata Toughees, whether you were paying fees or a fully sponsored student.



