You could see the joy and pride in these young boys’ eyes. Imagine the joy from a child from Turkana who was number one in their county but used to go to school barefoot,” she said, adding that it was through watching such boys that she understood the concept of dignity even in poverty.
Some of the boys would use soap and exercise books sparingly so that they could save them for their siblings back home.
The harambee culture demands publicity for acts of goodwill, even as the Good Book, which a majority profess to follow, frowns upon it.
We may not be able to match the Starehe model, but we can try. We can start by thwarting the urge to showcase our acts of charity on social media. Can you imagine anything more humiliating? Giving should not be a dignity-fracturing affair.
Keeping charitable acts off social media won’t be sufficient to fix what ails us, but it will be a good start.
